column.name: definition
column.value: A study that involves the synthesis of the archaeological history of investigation and culture history of a location or area.

column.name: definition
column.value: A study that involves research and analysis of archaeological resources held in a museum, historical society or other repository.

column.name: definition
column.value: An activity that involves discussions and meetings with communities, stakeholders, and other interested parties for the purpose of describing proposed archaeological activities and eliciting their comments, perspectives and feedback.

column.name: definition
column.value: An activity employed to gather a general impression of the nature and distribution of archaeological or cultural resources in an area. Relatively little field work is conducted in relation to the size of the research area.

column.name: definition
column.value: Activities undertaken to plan and schedule future archaeological research.

column.name: definition
column.value: An activity that involves the rehabilitation of eroding, slumping, subsiding or otherwise deteriorating archaeological resources, including structures and building materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: An activity involving the review of records, files, and other information about the sites recorded in a particular area. Typically, such studies involve checking the site files and other archives in an agency's database, or SHPO's office, or State Archaeologist's office.

column.name: definition
column.value: A non-field study of archaeological theory, method or technique. These investigations may also include broadly synthetic regional studies.

column.name: definition
column.value: These are studies that examine aspects of the present or past natural environment to provide a context, often off-site, for interpreting archaeological resources. Sometimes reported in stand-alone volumes representing significant research, such investigations may include geomorphological, paleontological, or palynological work.

column.name: definition
column.value: This is research that focuses on the systematic description and analysis of cultural systems or lifeways. These studies of contemporary people and cultures rely heavily on participant observation as well as interviews, oral histories, and review of relevant documents. Ethnoarchaeological studies are a subset of this kind of research that investigate correlations between traditional contemporary cultures and patterns in the archaeological record.

column.name: definition
column.value: These are studies of biological aspects of human individuals, groups, or cultural systems, including a broad range of topics describing and analyzing human physiology, osteology, diet, disease, and origins research.

column.name: definition
column.value: Descriptive and analytical research that documents, describes, and/or interprets detailed data on historic structures in an area, including images and floor plans.

column.name: definition
column.value: This kind of research includes systematic description and analysis of changes in cultural systems through time, using historical documents and oral and traditional histories. Ethnohistoric studies typically deal with time periods of initial or early contact between different cultural systems, for example, European explorers or early colonists and indigenous cultures.

column.name: definition
column.value: These are investigations of the past using written records and other documents. Evidence from the records are compared, judged for veracity, placed in chronological or topical sequence, and interpreted in light of preceding, contemporary, and subsequent events.

column.name: definition
column.value: Visits to a site to record archaeological resources and their conditions and recover finds that may have come to light since a previous visit. Also refers to regular or systematic monitoring and recording of the condition of a site, checking for signs of vandalism, other human intervention, and natural processes that may have damaged the resource.

column.name: definition
column.value: Observations and investigations conducted during any ground disturbing operation carried out for non-archaeological reasons (e.g. construction, land-leveling, wild land fire-fighting, etc.) that may reveal and/or damage archaeological deposits.

column.name: definition
column.value: This is an investigation employed to systematically gather data on the general presence or absence of archaeological resources, to define resource types, or to estimate the distribution of resources in an area. These studies may provide a general understanding of the resources in an area. This includes the description, analysis, and specialized studies of artifacts and samples recovered during survey.

column.name: definition
column.value: These investigations include fieldwork undertaken to identify the archaeological resources in a given area and to collect information sufficient to evaluate the resource(s) and develop treatment recommendations. Such investigations typically determine the number, location, distribution and condition of archaeological resources. This includes the description, analysis, and specialized studies of artifacts and samples recovered during site testing.

column.name: definition
column.value: These investigations include substantial field investigation of an archaeological site (or sites) involving the removal, and systematic recording of, archaeological matrix. These activities often mitigate the adverse effects of a public undertaking. This includes the description, analysis, and specialized studies of artifacts and samples recovered during excavations.

column.name: definition
column.value: These investigations include field and/or document and records reviews to gather data on the presence and type of historic structures and provide a general understanding of architectural and cultural resources in an area.

column.name: definition
column.value: Historic or prehistoric artifacts made from pottery or fired clay

column.name: definition
column.value: Lithic artifacts such as tools, flakes, shatter, or debitage

column.name: definition
column.value: Material collected for use with dating techniques such as radiocarbon, dendrochronology or archaeomagnetism

column.name: definition
column.value: Rocks showing evidence of intense heating or burning, carbon staining, or other indications of changes due to heat.

column.name: definition
column.value: Historic or prehistoric artifacts made from glass

column.name: definition
column.value: Lithic artifact formed or finished by polishing the body or edges with an abrasive

column.name: definition
column.value: Materials used for construction (e.g., brick, wood, adobe)

column.name: definition
column.value: The remains of any part of a human

column.name: definition
column.value: Plant remains such as fruit, seeds, buds, or other plant parts.

column.name: definition
column.value: Any prehistoric or historic artifact made of metal (e.g., iron, copper, gold, silver, etc.)

column.name: definition
column.value: Natural inorganic substance possessing a definite chemical composition in a crystalline form.

column.name: definition
column.value: Use for any microscopic plant remains

column.name: definition
column.value: Modified or unmodified objects made from mollusc shell.

column.name: definition
column.value: Modified or unmodified objects made from the roots, trunk, or branches of trees or shrubs.

column.name: definition
column.value: The locations and/or archaeological remains of a building or buildings used for human habitation. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: The locations and/or archaeological remains of features or sites related to resource extraction, commerce, industry, or transportation. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: The archaeological features or locations used for human burial or funerary activities. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: label
column.value: Funerary and Burial Structures or Features

column.name: definition
column.value: The locations and/or archaeological remains of a building or buildings used for purposes other than human habitation. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A localized area containing evidence of human activity. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Designs, whether carved, scraped, pecked or painted, applied to free-standing stones, cave walls, or the earth’s surface. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: The locations and/or archaeological remains of ships, boats, or other vessels, or the facilities related to shipping or sailing.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of multiple structures or features, that were inhabited by humans in the past. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A relatively small, short-term human habitation occupied by a relatively small group.

column.name: definition
column.value: Relatively small, self-contained groups of dwellings and associated structures providing shelter and a home base for its human inhabitants. Typically occupied for a number of years or decades, and in some cased for centuries.

column.name: definition
column.value: Larger settlements with more dwellings and a wide variety of other kinds of structures. These settlements typically have internally organized infrastructure of streets or walkways and water and waste-disposal systems. Typically occupied for decades or centuries.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of buildings that were inhabited by humans in the past. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A temporary structure, made out of brush, with a roof and walls, built to provide shelter for occupants or contents (e.g., wikieup, ki).

column.name: definition
column.value: Natural hollow or opening beneath earth's surface, with an aperture to the surface, showing evidence of human use. Caves may or may not have been modified for or by human use. A cave differs from a rockshelter in depth, penetration, and the constriction of the opening.

column.name: definition
column.value: A relatively small dwelling occupied by a single nuclear or extended family. May appear archaeologically as a stone foundation or pattern of post molds.

column.name: definition
column.value: A slightly raised, mounded area of earth or rock built to provide a platform for a single domestic structure.

column.name: definition
column.value: The remains of a small surface structure constructed of brush (wattle) and mud (daub).

column.name: definition
column.value: A long, relatively narrow multi-family dwelling, best known as a typical village dwelling used by Iroquois Confederacy tribes.

column.name: definition
column.value: Semi-subterranean habitation that may have an oval, round or rectangular shape. Typically with a dome-like covering constructed using a wood frame covered by branches, reeds, other vegetation and earth.

column.name: definition
column.value: Remains of a contiguous, multi-room habitation structure. Typically constructed of stone, mud brick or adobe. Usually manifests archaeologically as a surface mound of construction debris, sometimes with visible wall alignments.

column.name: definition
column.value: Overhang, indentation, or alcove formed naturally by rock fall or in a rock face; generally not of great depth. Rockshelters may or may not be modified with structural elements for human use.

column.name: definition
column.value: All temporary shelters (e.g. lean-tos, windbreaks, brush enclosures, sun shades etc.).

column.name: definition
column.value: Circular pattern (sometimes outlined with rocks) left when a tipi or tent is dismantled.

column.name: definition
column.value: A relatively high (over 1 meter), flat-topped mound, frequently constructed in several stages on which one or more structures were placed. Platform mounds are constructed using soil, shell, or refuse. They may incorporate earlier, filled-in structures in their substructure.

column.name: definition
column.value: A low mounded area of shell built to provide a platform for one or more domestic structures.

column.name: definition
column.value: Relatively small dwellings, typically circular or rectangular and about 3 meters tall, made of wooden frames with bases dug into the soil and covered with woven mats or sheets of birchbark. The frames could be shaped like a dome, a cone, or a rectangle with an arched roof.

column.name: definition
column.value: Relatively large, rectangular dwellings made of long, flat planks of cedar wood lashed to a substantial wooden frame. Typical of permanent villages of Indian tribes living in the American Northwest during the historic contact period and earlier.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of features or facilities, that were used for horticulture, agriculture, or animal husbandry. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Specified area containing evidence that is associated with historic governmental activity.

column.name: definition
column.value: An area of land, often enclosed, used for cultivation. Fields are not necessarily formally bounded, and may be identifiable based on diagnostic features such as boundary markers or raised beds.

column.name: definition
column.value: Ditch or interrelated group of ditches, acequias, head gates, and drains that constitute an irrigation system for individual watering and irrigation features.

column.name: definition
column.value: An enclosure for confining livestock. May be constructed of any material and incorporate natural features or vegetation as part of the enclosure.

column.name: definition
column.value: Natural or artificial lake in which water can be stored for future use.

column.name: definition
column.value: An artificially created, more or less level area cut into the side of a hill. The edge may be bordered by stone or other material to prevent erosion.

column.name: definition
column.value: A device which controls the flow of water, particularly run-off. Includes check dams, flumes, gabions, head gates, drop structures, and riprap.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of features or facilities, that were used for commercial or industrial purposes. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A relative large structure in which goods were manufactured or prepared for commercial distribution.

column.name: definition
column.value: A relatively small facility (one or a few rooms) for processing grain, wood, or other materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: A mill for processing grain, typically powered by water or wind.

column.name: definition
column.value: A mill for processing timber or wood.

column.name: definition
column.value: A structure designed for catching fish. Sometimes constructed as a fence or enclosure of wooden stakes or stones, placed in a river, lake, wetland or tidal estuary.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of features or facilities, that were used for hunting or trapping animals. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Concentration of faunal remains resulting from human hunting activity.

column.name: definition
column.value: Small, unroofed structure expediently constructed out of natural rock and/or wood as camouflage.

column.name: definition
column.value: A cliff or other natural drop off where large game can be stampeded over the edge.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations used for the extraction of metals, ores, minerals, or other materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: An excavation made in the earth for the purpose of digging out metallic ores, coal, salt, precious stones or other resources. Includes portals, adits, vent shafts, prospects, and haulage tunnels.

column.name: definition
column.value: The remains of facilities or equipment, usually above ground, used for processing or storing mined materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: Outcrops of lithic material that have been mined or otherwise utilized to obtain lithic raw materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: The archaeological remains of identifiable paths or routes between two or more locations. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: label
column.value: Road, Trail, and Related Structures or Features

column.name: definition
column.value: A structure with one or more intervals under it to span a river or other space.

column.name: definition
column.value: A road or pathway constructed from packed earth, stone, or shell, usually across a wetland or small water body.

column.name: definition
column.value: Identifiable, linear archaeological remains of unknown function.

column.name: definition
column.value: Segment(s) of railroad tracks or railroad bed.

column.name: definition
column.value: A prepared, formal way used for the passage of humans, animals, and/or vehicles. These include examples such as Chacoan roads.

column.name: definition
column.value: An informal foot path used for the passage of humans, animals, and/or vehicles, defined and worn by use without formal construction or maintenance.

column.name: definition
column.value: A formal location for burying the dead.

column.name: definition
column.value: An artificial mound constructed using earth, shell, or stone for the purpose of holding one or more burials. Frequently containing several episodes of construction and burials from different periods of time.

column.name: definition
column.value: A structure in which recently deceased human bodies were placed so that the flesh and other soft tissue would decompose prior to final interment of the remains.

column.name: definition
column.value: A location containing a human burial, spatially removed from other archaeological evidence.

column.name: definition
column.value: A secondary burial of multiple individuals.

column.name: definition
column.value: An unmarked human interment in a subterranean pit.

column.name: definition
column.value: A prepared, architecturally distinctive structure, normally sub-surface, often containing multiple interments. Use for features such as shaft tombs.

column.name: definition
column.value: An unroofed structure associated with the playing of the Mesoamerican ball game, found in the American southwest and parts of Mesoamerica.

column.name: definition
column.value: Buildings, or the archaeological remains of features or facilities, that were used for religious purposes. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Remains of a prehistoric building or location designed for public religious services.

column.name: definition
column.value: Remains of a historic building or location designed for public religious services.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of buildings that were associated with communal or public activities.

column.name: definition
column.value: Specified area containing evidence that is associated with prehistoric communal or public activity.

column.name: definition
column.value: Specified area containing evidence that is associated with historic communal or public activity.

column.name: definition
column.value: A multi-story building with massive masonry or adobe walls, found in the Chacoan and Hohokam regions of the American southwest.

column.name: definition
column.value: Locations, or the remains of buildings that were associated with governmental activities.

column.name: definition
column.value: Specified area containing evidence that is associated with prehistoric governmental activity.

column.name: definition
column.value: Circular or rectangular ceremonial structure. May be subterranean or part of a surface room block.

column.name: definition
column.value: Military-related structure constructed for various purposes (personnel barracks, testing, aircraft storage or landing, etc.).

column.name: definition
column.value: An above ground construction of earth, shell or other material, undifferentiated as to function.

column.name: definition
column.value: An above ground prepared surface on which a non-residential structure is built.

column.name: definition
column.value: A non-residential cultural construction made from earth, shell or other materials, often formed to enclose or demarcate an area, or, in the case of causeways, to link areas. Examples include shell rings.

column.name: definition
column.value: A defensive construction made from earth, shell or other materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: An above ground construction of earth, shell or other material, built in the shape of geometric, animal or other symbolic forms. Prominent examples include Effigy Mounds National Monument and Serpent Mound.

column.name: definition
column.value: A large, circular area defined by a perimeter of mounded shell (often several meters in height), for example, Archaic Period shell ring sites in the American southeast.

column.name: definition
column.value: A large and/or ornate building, normally associated with a high ranking family or individual.

column.name: definition
column.value: An enclosure, constructed of timbers or posts driven into ground, or otherwise walled.

column.name: definition
column.value: An area which may be partially or completely enclosed by structural remains (standing or collapsed), used for community activities. May contain temporary structures (e.g. sun shades or ramadas) as well as special activity areas (e.g. milling bins, hearths).

column.name: definition
column.value: A massive structure, typically with triangular outer surfaces that converge at the top. Often flat-topped to accommodate public gatherings and/or buildings.

column.name: definition
column.value: A series of steps allowing access to a different level. Use for toe/hand holds, stairs, ladders, etc.

column.name: definition
column.value: Architectural remnant of a building of unknown form or function.

column.name: definition
column.value: Architectural remnant of a prehistoric building of unknown form or function. Use more specific term if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Architectural remnant of a historic building of unknown form or function. Use more specific term if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: Small enclosure or hut used for steam baths, usually ephemeral in construction. Often with fire-cracked rock and/or hearths in association.

column.name: definition
column.value: Monumental architecture constructed from stone or other materials, and used for religious and/or political purposes.

column.name: definition
column.value: Prehistoric lithic and/or ceramic scatters with no features.

column.name: definition
column.value: Mound or stack of rocks used to mark significant locations (e.g., boundaries or claims).

column.name: definition
column.value: A structure that creates a boundary, barrier, or enclosure. Construction materials can vary widely and may include unmodified natural materials (such as brush).

column.name: definition
column.value: Discolored area of soil, often including charcoal, ash deposits or fire cracked rock, exhibiting evidence of use in association with fire. May be bounded (e.g., rock ring) or ill-defined.

column.name: definition
column.value: A find spot containing a single artifact.

column.name: definition
column.value: A find spot containing a single cultural feature.

column.name: definition
column.value: Oven used to bake food, fire pottery, or thermally alter other materials (e.g., bricks, lithic materials).

column.name: definition
column.value: An archaeological refuse deposit containing the broken or discarded remains of human activities. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A large, dense concentrations, often mounded, of fire cracked rock (FCR), usually associated with large scale plant processing. Although other cultural materials may be present in the midden, FCR is usually predominant.

column.name: definition
column.value: A surficial archaeological deposit containing discarded artifacts and other cultural materials. Midden deposits normally contain ashy or charcoal-stained sediments, and domestic-related items such as sherds, lithic debitage, and bone.

column.name: definition
column.value: An archaeological deposit composed primarily of discarded mollusk shells.

column.name: definition
column.value: A substantial concentration of refuse, built up as a result of multiple episodes of deposition.

column.name: definition
column.value: A facility made or used for grinding or processing plant materials. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A pecked or ground concavity in a large boulder or outcrop, including both bedrock mortar and bedrock metate.

column.name: definition
column.value: An enclosed container used for milling plant material. May be above ground or partially or completely underground.

column.name: definition
column.value: A discrete excavation directly attributable to human activity. Use more specific term(s) if possible.

column.name: definition
column.value: A discrete excavation directly attributable to human activity that was used for the disposal of discarded artifacts, ecofacts and other cultural materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: An enclosed space used to heat objects placed within its bounds. Includes earth ovens, oven pits, mud ovens, and bread ovens.

column.name: definition
column.value: A discrete excavation directly attributable to human activity used for storing artifacts, ecofacts and other cultural materials.

column.name: definition
column.value: One or more upright posts, remains of posts, or sockets usually associated with a larger feature or structure such as a building, fence, corral, stockade, pen, etc.

column.name: definition
column.value: Group of rocks which appear to have some cultural association. Use for possible walls, wall-like phenomena, human produced architectural oddities, rock piles, etc.

column.name: definition
column.value: Designs created on the ground surface by arranging rocks or other materials, or by scraping or altering the earth surface. Usually on a large scale.

column.name: definition
column.value: Design scratched, pecked, or scraped into a rock surface.

column.name: definition
column.value: Design drawn in pigment upon an unprepared or ground rock surface.

column.name: definition
column.value: The remains of facilities or equipment related to boats, ships, or shipping. Use for dock, wharf etc.

column.name: definition
column.value: The remains of a ship, boat or other vessel.

column.name: definition
column.value: The underwater remains of an aircraft.
